definition.value: A member of the class of hydroxybiphenyls that is biphenyl substituted by a hydroxy group at position 2. It is generally used as a post-harvest fungicide for citrus fruits.

A nitrogen oxide consisting of linear unsymmetrical molecules with formula N2O. While it is the most used gaseous anaesthetic in the world, its major commercial use, due to its solubility under pressure in vegetable fats combined with its non-toxicity in low concentrations, is as an aerosol spray propellant and aerating agent for canisters of 'whipped' cream.
The L-enantiomer of aspartic acid.
An organic phosphonate having O-1-carboxyvinyl and C-carboxy substituents.
A glycosylglucose consisting of two glucose units linked via a beta(1->4) bond.
The D-enantiomer of glutamine.
A nitroaniline carrying a nitro group at position 4.

The R-enantiomer of 3-hydroxybutyric acid. Involved in the synthesis and degradation of ketone bodies, it can be used as an energy source by the brain during hypoglycaemia, and for the synthesis of biodegradable plastics.
The glycolaldehyde derived from ethylene glycol. The parent of the class of glycolaldehydes.
A amino cyclitol glycoside that consists of streptidine having a disaccharyl moiety attached at the 4-position. The parent of the streptomycin class
A compound in which a carbonyl group is bonded to two carbon atoms: R2C=O (neither R may be H).
An sn-glycero-3-phosphate compound having a single unspecified acyl group at either position 1 or position 2.
A compound in which a carbohydrate component is covalently bound to a protein component.
The (1R,2R,3R)-diastereomer of prephytoene diphosphate.

A benzenoid aromatic compound that consists of two benzene rings connected by a single covalent bond. Biphenyl occurs naturally in coal tar, crude oil, and natural gas. Formerly used as a fungicide for citrus crops.
A dimethoxybenzene that is benzaldehyde substituted by methoxy groups at positions 3 and 4. It is found in peppermint, ginger, raspberry, and other fruits.
An alkyl-sn-glycerol 3-phosphate in which the alkyl group is at position 1 of the sn-glycerol.
The meso-diastereomer of butane-1,2,3,4-tetrol.
The L-enantiomer of serine.
A short-chain fatty acid anion that is the conjugate base of hexanoic acid (also known as caproic acid).
An N-acetylmannosamine in open-chain aldehyde form with D-configuration.
An amino-acid betaine that is butanoate substituted with a hydroxy group at position C-3 and a trimethylammonium group at C-4.
A dicarboxylic acid dianion obtained by the deprotonation of both the carboxy groups of adipic acid.
A four-carbon alkane-alpha,omega-diamine. It is obtained by the breakdown of amino acids and is responsible for the foul odour of putrefying flesh.
A pentitol (five-carbon sugar alcohol) having meso-configuration, being derived from xylose by reduction of the carbonyl group.
A pyridinecarboxamide that is pyridine in which the hydrogen at position 3 is replaced by a carboxamide group.
A derivative of puromycin lacking the O-methyl group on the tyrosyl residue.
A tetrasaccharide consisting of sucrose having an alpha-D-galactosyl-(1->6)-alpha-D-galactosyl moiety attached at the 6-position of the glucose.
An arenecarbaldehyde that consists of benzene bearing a single formyl substituent; the simplest aromatic aldehyde and parent of the class of benzaldehydes.
A secondary aliphatic amine where both N-substituents are methyl.
A purine 2'-deoxyribonucleoside having guanine as the nucleobase.
A primary alcohol comprising an allyl core with a hydroxy substituent at the 1-position and a phenyl substituent at the 3-position (geometry of the C=C bond unspecified).
A dihydroxybenzoic acid having the two hydroxy groups at the 2- and 5-positions.
The L-enantiomer of isoleucine.
An optically active form of asparagine having L-configuration.
A dipeptide formed from glycine residues.

Pyrrolidine in which the pro-S hydrogen at position 2 is substituted by a carboxylic acid group. L-Proline is the only one of the twenty DNA-encoded amino acids which has a secondary amino group alpha to the carboxyl group. It is an essential component of collagen and is important for proper functioning of joints and tendons. It also helps maintain and strengthen heart muscles.
A butenoic acid having the double bond at position C-2.
A hydroxycoumarin that is umbelliferone substituted by a methyl group at position 4.
A sulfur-containing amino acid consisting of a glycine core with a 2-mercaptoethyl side-chain.
A cresol with the methyl substituent at position 3. It is a minor urinary metabolite of toluene.
An aldohexose used as a source of energy and metabolic intermediate.
